Q20. Explaining Precision, Recall and F1 score¶

In [173]:
print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.95      0.91      0.93      1342
           1       0.46      0.63      0.53       158

    accuracy                           0.88      1500
   macro avg       0.71      0.77      0.73      1500
weighted avg       0.90      0.88      0.89      1500

Precision = True positives/ (True positive + False positive) Precision is the % accuracy in the number of Trues predicted. In this case, it is

  1. the number of people who were accurately predicted to not have a personal loan vs the total number of people predicted to not have a personal loan
  2. the number of people who were accurately predicted having a personal loan vs the total number of people predicted to have a personal loan

Recall = True positives/ (True positives + False negatives) Recall is the % accuracy in the number of actual Trues. In this case, it is

  1. the number of people who were accurately predicted to not have a personal loan vs the actual total number of people who did not have a personal loan
  2. the number of people who were accurately predicted having a personal loan vs the actual total number of people who did have a personal loan

The precision and recall is lower for the 1s as the data is signficantly biased towards the 0s (1300 + cases). This means that there is a lot of actual 1s (had personal loan) that were classified as 0s (do not have). This affects both the precision and recall. This can be mitigated using lower thresholds or weighting the samples. In our case, we are proceeding with lower thresholds.

F1 score = 2 (precision recall) / (precision + recall) The F1 score is a good mix of precision and recall. It works better than the accuracy measure and can be used when we need to balance both precision and recall </font>

The difference between the models¶

  1. Naive Bayes is a probabilistic model which assumes that all factors are independent. The calculation of probabilistic impact ensures that impact of irrelevant variables is 0. It may be the best generalizer in this group
  2. Logistic regression is a statistical algorithm that leverages an activation function/equation. This helps it determine the output class. It is more susceptible to irrelevant data in the data set. This is slower than the Naive Bayes, but faster than KNN.

  3. KNN is an algorithm that leverages vector spatial calculus to determine 'n' nearest neighbours. And based on the nearest neighbours, the point is classified. This is a simple algorithm, although its calculations may become complex if k or the data set increases. This is the slowest algorithm in this set.

    </font>

Q27. Discuss some of the key hyper parameters available for the selected algorithm. What values did you initialize these parameters to?¶

  1. Our selected algorithm is the Logistic regression for the reason that it has the largest AUC in the ROC curve. This means that Logistic regression will provide a better output than the other two algorithms.
  2. The key hyperparameters used were 'C', and the 'penalty'. 'C' is the inverse of regularization strength and 'penalty' is the norm that specifies penalization (lasso, ridge or elasticnet). We initialized them to their defaults in the first attempt and later gave them the range [0.01, 0.1,1,10,100,1000] and ['l1' (Lasso), 'l2' (Ridge), 'elasticnet']. The solver was initialized to 'liblinear' which is the recommendation for smaller datasets

  3. Other parameters include fit_intercept, intercept_scaling, class_weight and more mentioned in the documentation https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html

    </font>

Q28. Regularization techniques used for the model¶

We used several regularization techniques in this exercise

  1. We first trimmed down our data using MinMaxScaler and scaled it into the range 0-1 for 4 columns (Age, Income, Mortgage, CCAvg)
  2. We then used cost imposition 'C' to penalize complexity of the equation/activation function in the logistic regression
  3. Further, we used a threshold to normalize and reduce the bias in the dataset injected due to the large number of 0s in the dataset </font>

For range estimation, we use the Z-Score to calculate the confidence interval

we will use our current accuracy rate to find the potential error </font>

interval = z_value sqrt((error(1-error))/n)
